Entries.default: "The handsome fish leaps into my net once again, I say." A smile rises to Auāta's face as she catches sight of Tekēhu.
"I take it you two are acquainted?"
"Ekera, we were. Briefly and purposefully." Tekēhu folds his arms and grins.
"I did not think you'd swim back, fish."
"Rotten. Pugnant. All the reasons you didn't fight when I gave you back to the sea."
"Not pleasure? Tell me what they have done with the true Tekēhu."
"You are a delight as ever, I say. Keep the tribe safe, Auāta."
"It is what I do. You keep swimming, Tekēhu. It is what you do." She sighs and gives him a warm look before turning away.
"You're awfully chummy with Tekēhu even though he isn't Wahaki."
"Ekera. But look at him." She thumbs over to Tekēhu.
